To determine which nuclide has an NMR frequency of 115.5 MHz in a 20.0 T magnetic field, we need to calculate the gyromagnetic ratio (γ) using the given formula and then compare it with known gyromagnetic ratios of the given nuclides.

1. Rearrange the NMR frequency formula to solve for γ:
   \[
   γ = \frac{2πν}{B}
   \]

2. Substitute the given values into the formula:
   \[
   γ = \frac{2π \times 115.5 \text{ MHz}}{20.0 \text{ T}}
   \]

3. Calculate the gyromagnetic ratio (γ):
   \[
   γ = \frac{2π \times 115.5 \times 10^6 \text{ Hz}}{20.0 \text{ T}}
   \]
   \[
   γ = \frac{2 \times 3.14159 \times 115.5 \times 10^6}{20.0}
   \]
   \[
   γ ≈ \frac{725.6 \times 10^6}{20.0}
   \]
   \[
   γ ≈ 36.28 \times 10^6 \text{ rad T}^{-1} \text{ s}^{-1}
   \]

4. Compare the calculated γ with known gyromagnetic ratios of the given nuclides:
   - \(^{17}\text{O}\): γ ≈ -5.772 \times 10^6 rad T^{-1} s^{-1}
   - \(^{19}\text{F}\): γ ≈ 25.181 \times 10^6 rad T^{-1} s^{-1}
   - \(^{29}\text{Si}\): γ ≈ -5.319 \times 10^6 rad T^{-1} s^{-1}
   - \(^{31}\text{P}\): γ ≈ 17.235 \times 10^6 rad T^{-1} s^{-1}

The calculated γ (36.28 \times 10^6 rad T^{-1} s^{-1}) does not match any of the given nuclides exactly. However, it is closest to the gyromagnetic ratio of \(^{19}\text{F}\) (25.181 \times 10^6 rad T^{-1} s^{-1}). Given the options, \(^{19}\text{F}\) is the most reasonable match.
